default&#xa0;
defaultQ494 default&#xa0; 
defaultLindsay Roy:default 
defaultHow
default do you explain the divergence between police-recorded crime data and the Crime Survey for 
defaultEngland
default and 
defaultWales
default?  What action have you taken in relation to that?
defaultSir Andrew Dilnotdefault: The action we have taken in relation to that is primarily that we have de
default&#x2011;
defaultdesignated the police-recorded crime data, because that is one of the bases on which it seems to us 
defaultunsatisfactory
default.  The possible reasons for that are as described by Mr
default&#xa0;
defaultFlatley earlier on: performance-related target regimes; the possibility that the complexity causes problems; the possibility that the training needs to be better; and the possibility that Force Crime Registrars do not have as much authority and domain as they need to have.  In the end, though, the core point must be that if there is a problem, it is in the interests not just of the whole country but also of the police force to get this right, because until we have accurate data, not only do we not know how well the police force is doing from the outside, but it will be very hard for the police force to run itself effectively.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ495 default&#xa0; 
